
## TOPs FFmpeg Movies to Frameset Images

### Example HIP: 

* TOPs\_FFmpeg\_Movies\_to\_Frameset\_Images\_V001.hip

### Description:

Use FFMpeg to batch convert movie files into image sequences.

This input videos are formatted like:  

	"$HIP/videos/Camera.[0001-0200].mp4"

The images are converted by FFmpeg and written to a "frameset" folder that is formatted as:  

	"$HIP/images/####/Camera.NNNN.tiff"

The symbols "\#\#\#\#" represent the image sequence frame number.  
The symbols "NNNN" represent the camera array view number.

This results in an end output that looks  like:  

	"$HIP/images/[0001-0153]/Camera.[0001-200].tiff"

#### FFmpeg Extract Images

Input Source: Custom File Path  
File Path: \`@filesMP4\`

Controls:  
Frames per Second: 30  
Output File Pattern: $HIP/images/Camera\_\`@ViewNum\`.%04d.tiff  
File Tag: file/image

FFmpeg:  
FFmpeg Command: Extra FFmpeg tags can be added at a later date. These tags include "-q:v1" for better JPEG/TIFF image compression quality, along with \-ss for a video start frame/timecode, and \-vcount for the number of frames to extract from the source movies.
